CTF-200-02

Target IP: 192.168.250.178
Challenge Description: N/A.

Reconnaissance


Performing a port scan shows there are two TCP ports open on the target machine: SSH and HTTP, as shown above.


Doing an aggressive port scan against the open ports returns the result above. I will start enumeration with the HTTP application on port 80.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

The webpage above is displayed for this web application. This web application allows file upload. Maybe it is vulnerable to file upload attacks?


I downloaded a jpg image on my machine and uploaded this file using this web application. After uploading it, I received the output above. I did a directory search to identify the location of the uploaded file, but I had no luck. Is the string 6.9.6-4 the application version on the target machine, or the version of the image I uploaded? Apparently, the imagemagick tool has another tool called identifier which can be used to extract information of images.


Doing a Google search for ImageMagic 6.9.6-4 exploits, I obtained the GitHub ImageMagic issue above. It looks like this application version is vulnerable to command injection. The webpage above also contains the PoC to perform this exploit. Time to test it.

Exploitation


The target IP is 192.168.193.178 after reseting the box due to VPN issues. On my machine, I created an image called img.jpg. Then using the command in the image above, I created a reverse shell encoded malicious image file.


I started a listener on my machine at port 8443. After uploading the reverse-shell encoded image, I now have a foothold on the target machine, as shown above, with the session as www-data.

Privilege Escalation


Running the command find / -perm -u=s -type f 2>/dev/null shows the /usr/bin/strace has SUID bit set. I can use this to escalated my privileges.


And now I have a root shell on the target machine by using the misconfigured /usr/bin/strace binary to spawn a root shell, as shown above.
